In addition, Vertex AI has helped to speed up collecting, processing, and analyzing data, drastically reducing the time it takes to gain insights from weeks down to hours. 

*Results:* With Google‚Äôs data cloud, Lowe‚Äôs now has the data foundations it needs to develop new AI capabilities that facilitate remarkable new ways to unlock and distribute expertise, enabling more than 300,000 associates across its 1,700 stores to assist customers during the home improvement journeys with greater knowledge and confidence.

title: New Way Now: Deloitte stops state-sponsored cyberattack; identifies threats 66% faster with Google
author: Google Cloud
description:
*Featured in this video:* Caroline Honeycombe, Director of Cyber Incident Response at Deloitte, and Paul Beverley-Paddock, Director, Security Operations Lead at Deloitte

*Executive summary:* Deloitte, one of the biggest and oldest global consulting firms, tackles a huge range of challenges for clients ‚Äî from boardroom strategy to technical implementation. One recent win was hugely impactful: the firm helped stop a state-sponsored cyberattack before it could affect public and digital services across Europe. Stopping that attack and reclaiming highly sensitive compromised data depended on a solution built using both the Google Security Operations and Google Threat Intelligence platforms along with Gemini. The Deloitte team ingested billions of log data points into Google SecOps, then used Gemini to ask questions of the data to decide how to tackle particular threats. That new visibility and searchability turned data points into prioritized actions the team could take immediately to counter and remove the threat. Deloitte‚Äôs AI-powered Illuminator also visualizes data so teams can identify and neutralize potential threats. The new solution has brought huge gains for level 1 and 2 analysts, who can identify threats 66% more efficiently by analyzing alerts and identifying whether they‚Äôre a true positive or false positive and what, if any, action should be taken.

*Challenge:* The complexity and scale of data, and sophistication of bad actors, have grown concurrently to offer new challenges for security teams. The foiled cyberattack at Deloitte‚Äôs client came from sophisticated threat actors, though they used typical IT organization tools that made it easier to hide the threat. For Deloitte, the key ingredients in building a system to counter these new, fast-moving threats were speed and the ability to parse tremendous amounts of data immediately. 

*Solution:* The integration of SecOps and Threat Intelligence meant that Deloitte‚Äôs team could quickly identify who the threat actor was, and take action. Along with these Google Cloud Security tools, the natural language search capabilities of Gemini in SecOps allow the Deloitte team to ask questions in real time, such as whether and what type of detection rule should be written. Those answers brought both speedy insights and prioritized actions so the team could remove the threat and re-secure the environment. Along with those short-term reactions, the Deloitte team can now build improved client capabilities so they‚Äôre more protected in the long term and better able to react to threats going forward.

*Results:* Gemini AI‚Äôs capabilities applied to massive amounts of data now let Deloitte‚Äôs cybersecurity clients‚Äô teams quickly identify and remove threats before they can attack and cause any number of disruptions. This combination of AI and security technology has helped Deloitte reimagine their entire approach to the challenges of modern threat detection. The team is able to act faster than ever before with previously unimaginable depth and hugely increased efficiency in identifying threats.

*Key takeaways and highlights from our interview with Caroline Honeycombe, Director of Cyber Incident Response at Deloitte, and Paul Beverley-Paddock, Director, Security Operations Lead at Deloitte:*

‚Üí ‚ÄúIt essentially gave us speed, scale, depth. We can act faster than we could before with a depth we couldn‚Äôt have dreamed of. We‚Äôre able to help clients ‚Äòshift left‚Äô and put threat intelligence at the heart of everything we do.‚Äù ‚ÄîPaul Beverley-Paddock

‚Üí ‚ÄúBringing in Google allowed us get insights into what we were facing and very quickly reduce billions of data points into very short, prioritized actions that we were able to take to remove the threat actor from the environment, re-secure the environment, and build the client‚Äôs capability so they‚Äôre more protected and in a better position to react going forward.‚Äù ‚ÄîPaul Beverley-Paddock

‚Üí ‚ÄúBeing able to use Google SecOps to actually search what we‚Äôre after has been super powerful. And we‚Äôve now got a really nice picture of forensics data, log data, and threat intelligence in one place.‚Äù ‚ÄîCaroline Honeycombe

‚Üí ‚ÄúTaking AI as an example, Google is one step ahead of where technology is going and what is happening in the market. Google Cloud is helping Deloitte find a new way to hunt threats faster.‚Äù ‚ÄîCaroline Honeycombe

*Google Cloud products used:* Google Security Operations, Google Threat Intelligence, Gemini

title: New Way Now: ID.me fights fraud for over 145 million users ‚Äî powered by AlloyDB
author: Google Cloud
description:
*Featured in this video:* Kevin Liu, Cloud Platform Architect at ID.me

*Executive summary:* Identity management technology provider ID.me offers a single login product for its users to safely transact across the internet. The platform quickly grew from 50 million to 145 million users ‚Äî a tremendous increase that also brought challenges in supporting multitudes of data and related generative AI projects. After searching for the right cloud partner to handle those many terabytes of data, ID.me chose Google Cloud and shifted its biggest workloads to AlloyDB. This new infrastructure backbone has helped democratize data and empower users across the company to build better models, optimize queries and applications, and serve customers with true high availability. ID.me has built secure sign-on capabilities and better models, and can now prevent or remediate fraud in real time. 

*Challenge:* To offer its digital wallet safely and quickly to its growing base of millions of users, ID.me had to strengthen its data foundation. The company runs huge workloads that require high availability for terabytes of data, and previous databases had taken up data teams‚Äô time with self-management. ID.me has also built generative AI identities, which brought potential fraud risk, so they needed to add functionality to ensure that users are real people.

*Solution:* ID.me moved dozens of terabytes of data into Google Cloud‚Äôs AlloyDB database, which now runs workloads of more than 10 TB apiece. The secret sauce that makes AlloyDB work for ID.me: its ability to actually separate storage and compute. AlloyDB also allows for the creation of multiple read pools, one for each workload. That means that ID.me can isolate those sets of data into data clean rooms for validation, then remediate or prevent issues in real time. That‚Äôs essential to ensure that gen AI models only access trusted data.
 
*Results:* ID.me‚Äôs new powerful back-end has democratized data and led to massive scalability and availability, and they‚Äôve seen a price decrease in their infrastructure. Data engineers and DBAs can now focus on building and optimizing apps, and teams overall have saved tremendous amounts of time compared to previous self-managed database instances. ID.me has built better fraud prevention models and saved at least a billion dollars in fraud by IRS standards. 

*Key takeaways and highlights from our interview with Kevin Liu, Cloud Platform Architect at ID.me:*

‚Üí ‚ÄúEveryone loves AI right now, but if you don‚Äôt have a truly solid data layer, all of your AI models are going to be problematic.‚Äù

‚Üí ‚ÄúWhat we love best about Google Cloud is how much better a developer experience we have now. We go from zero to full product application in days vs. weeks now.‚Äù

‚Üí ‚ÄúUsing AlloyDB has truly opened up our data engineers and DBAs to help them optimize applications, optimize queries, or build in-place ML applications.‚Äù

*Google Cloud products used:* AlloyDB, AlloyDB AI

*Learn more:*

Costco chose Google Cloud‚Äôs data and AI tools and partnered with Accenture to build its Unified Data Platform. The new platform brings trusted data to its 175,000 users, helping them to make better, faster decisions. And suppliers can better understand member behavior through aggregated data, all with the same goal: bringing value to members and delighting them with the merchandise in any Costco warehouse. Using Vertex and Gemini AI capabilities was foundational to the new platform‚Äôs ability to empower and expand teams‚Äô work.

*Challenge:* Costco maintains massive amounts of data and needed a modern data and AI platform to add even more innovation, efficiency, and flexibility to help its teams meet their shared goal of bringing value to members. With so many partners, hyperscalers, and technologies available, and with so much data, Costco enlisted Accenture‚Äôs help in researching and creating the right omnichannel solution.

*Solution:* Costco knew they would need a large data and AI footprint, so Google Cloud‚Äôs product depth, hyperscale, cost-effectiveness, and native capabilities were the right fit. Costco‚Äôs team built a robust platform, allowing them to democratize data to teams across the company and open up new opportunities, such as helping merchandisers understand sales and inventory positions, track promotion performance, and improve return and other processes.

*Results:* The data team has already seen short-term wins with its unified platform, such as cutting the time required to create new audiences from several weeks to 30 minutes. Suppliers can access aggregated data about member shopping behavior to tailor their offerings. In the longer term, Costco is using data and AI technology to bring more value to members and to the bottom line. As Costco‚Äôs leadership prepares to profitably double the company size in the next decade, AI capabilities will be crucial for omnichannel measurement, flexibility, and speed.

*Key takeaways and highlights from our interview with Harish Rao, Global VP of Data and Analytics for Costco Wholesale:*

‚Üí ‚ÄúCostco's philosophy is to think about continuous improvement. This partnership is not just, ‚Äòscale and you‚Äôre done.‚Äô It‚Äôs about continuous innovation to deliver superior member experience. That is who we are at Costco, and that applies to everything.‚Äù 

‚Üí ‚ÄúThe digital transformation journey is nothing generic that you can pick from. It all depends on your core values and core principles. We go back to our core value proposition of delivering superior member experience, delivering great product and great value. The Looker Conversational Analytics API provides a transformative way to interact with data, moving beyond traditional dashboards by allowing users to ask questions in natural language (like "Show me top-selling products last quarter"). Powered by Gemini for Google Cloud, the API leverages the Looker semantic layer (LookML) to ensure that every query is accurate, governed, and based on consistent business definitions, thus acting as a single source of truth. This technology empowers developers to embed trusted, AI-powered analytics directly into custom applications, internal portals, or workflows‚Äîeliminating context switching, democratizing data access, and ultimately accelerating the speed at which organizations can make reliable, data-driven decisions.

title: New Way Now: Mobile services get smarter at LG U+ with help from Google AI
author: Google Cloud
description:
*Featured in this video:* SeokYoung Lee, Director, Head of Mobile Agent Services at LG U+

*Executive summary:* Mobile network operator LG U+ chose Google Cloud AI to enhance on-device features for its more than 18 million subscribers across South Korea. As LG U+ continually works to bring customers convenient, easy-to-use mobile devices, they‚Äôve used Gemini and Vertex AI to add call summarization, visual call interfaces, spam detection, and AI call answering for users. In the competitive telecom market, and as LG U+ prepares for international expansion, the company chose Google AI products to differentiate its services and grow revenue. 

*Challenge:* LG U+ aimed to expand its services beyond South Korea, but needed to add to its existing capabilities quickly to serve users in real time with helpful, convenient AI features.
 
*Solution:* The mobile agent services team integrated Gemini into its ixi-O phone agent for more actionable AI that can understand user intent and respond accordingly. The LG U+ ixi-O One agent pairs its own device AI ‚Äî which transcribes and records calls in real time ‚Äî with Gemini, which performs sophisticated analysis to summarize conversations and suggest follow-up actions. Next, the mobile agent team will use Vertex AI to add features that recommend responses during calls based on content searches, as well as retrieve relevant locations, objects and contextual information. 

*Results:* With newly expanded AI capabilities, LG U+ will expand internationally, partnering with both Google and other telecom companies. The team‚Äôs plans for the coming year include building even deeper data-driven customer understanding into its products and creating an advanced autonomous agent.
